          "body": "At the chapter's center stands a claim of remarkable theological density: 'We will surely die and are like water spilled on the ground which cannot be gathered up again. Yet God does not take away life, but plans ways so that the banished one will not be cast out from him' (14:14). The mortality statement is uncontested wisdom — death is irreversible, and the logic of blood-vengeance that perpetuates the cycle of killing only multiplies irreversible losses. But the woman presses beyond observation to theology: the God of Israel is not content to let the nadach — the thrust-away, the driven-out — remain permanently cast out. He *plans* or *devises* (*chashav*) ways for the return of the banished. The word *chashav* is used in Genesis 50:20 ('you meant evil against me, but God meant it for good') and Jeremiah 29:11 ('I know the plans I have for you'). God's purposeful, active scheming for the restoration of the scattered is one of Scripture's persistent themes (Deuteronomy 30:1-10; Luke 15:11-32). The irony of 2 Samuel 14 is that this profound theological truth is used as a manipulation tool. The woman is not wrong about God. But the same God who plans the return of the banished also required atonement and justice before restoration. David grants the return without the justice, and the chapter demonstrates what happens when a true theological principle is selectively applied: partial obedience produces the appearance of mercy while the underlying wound festers."
