        "excerpt": "Now Joab the son of Zeruiah perceived that the king's heart was inclined toward Absalom.",
        "body": "The chapter's opening verse identifies both the motive and the method of what follows. Joab *perceives* (*yada*) — the same verb for knowledge used of David's moral insight and of divine omniscience — that David's heart is inclined toward Absalom. This is political intelligence of the highest order: Joab reads the king's affect before the king has translated it into policy. The inclination is real (see 13:39), but it is paralyzed. David's characteristic response to family crisis throughout 2 Samuel 11-18 is strong feeling without decisive action. He is angry (13:21) but does not discipline; he mourns (13:36) but does not adjudicate; he longs (13:39) but does not recall.\n\nJoab's solution is characteristically pragmatic and characteristically flawed. He recruits a 'wise woman' from Tekoa — not a random deceiver but a recognized category of socially intelligent counselor. The title *chakham* (wise) in this context implies skill in rhetoric, social navigation, and the management of difficult conversations. Joab provides the script (14:3), but the woman's execution of it (14:4-17) demonstrates her own considerable craft: she improvises, escalates the legal pressure, and deploys theology in service of the political goal.\n\nThe narrator's framing is important: Joab 'put the words in her mouth' (14:3). This is precisely the formula used of false prophecy and political manipulation throughout the Hebrew Bible (cf. 1 Kings 22:13). The woman is not a prophet; Joab is not Nathan. The parable they deploy contains a true theological claim (14:14) embedded in a structure of deception. This is one of Scripture's most clear-eyed portrayals of how true things can be weaponized in the service of agendas that bypass justice.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Yada* (perceived, 14:1) — the full cognitive and perceptive range of the word is in play: Joab did not merely observe but understood the king's emotional state and its political implications. *Chakham* (wise woman, 14:2) — skill-wisdom, practical intelligence in social navigation, as distinct from Torah wisdom or prophetic insight."
