        "title": "The parable's progressive entrapment — argument from mercy to obligation",
        "range": "14:4-17",
        "excerpt": "Why then have you planned such a thing against the people of God? For in speaking this word the king is as one who is guilty, in that the king does not bring back his banished one.",
        "body": "The woman's audience with David unfolds in four phases, each tightening the rhetorical trap. Phase one (14:4-8): she presents her scenario and receives a general royal commitment — 'I will give orders concerning you.' Phase two (14:9-11): she escalates by taking the iniquity on herself and securing a sworn oath from the king in the LORD's name — 'As the LORD lives, not one hair of your son shall fall to the ground.' Phase three (14:12-17): the pivot. Having secured the oath, she shifts from the fictional widow to the actual situation: 'Why then have you planned such a thing against the people of God?' (14:13). The king who has just sworn by the LORD to protect a fictional son who killed his brother is now indicted by his own ruling for not restoring his actual son who killed his brother.\n\nVerse 14 is the woman's theological apex: 'We will surely die and are like water spilled on the ground which cannot be gathered up again. Yet God does not take away life, but devises ways so that the banished one will not be cast out from him.' The argument has three movements: (a) death is irreversible — continuing to pursue Absalom with blood-vengeance logic produces only more irreversible loss; (b) God himself seeks the restoration of the scattered — therefore the king who embodies divine justice should do the same; (c) David's failure to restore Absalom is therefore a failure to image the God whose justice he represents.\n\nThe argument is brilliant and partially valid. God does indeed seek the return of the banished — the theology of Deuteronomy 30:1-10, the parable of the Prodigal Son (Luke 15:11-32), and the entire prophetic tradition of exile-and-return confirm it. But the woman's argument bypasses the equally biblical insistence that restoration requires acknowledgment of sin and some form of justice. She is citing divine mercy selectively, in service of Joab's agenda, without the prophetic authorization that would make it a genuine word from the LORD. David's failure to see this distinction — to recognize that the woman's theology is true but her application is manipulated — is a significant failure of discernment.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Nadach* (banished, 14:13-14) — thrust away, driven out, scattered. The word carries connotations of being permanently exiled from community and covenant. *Chashav* (devises ways, 14:14) — purposeful, intelligent planning; the same root as in Gen 50:20 and Jer 29:11. God's active plotting for restoration is the chapter's most significant theological claim."
