        "body": "The chapter's most illuminating exchange occurs in verses 18-20. David does not yield because he is convinced; he yields because he is politically outmaneuvered. He asks immediately and directly: 'Is the hand of Joab with you in all this?' (14:19). The question reveals that David's political intelligence has been functioning throughout the parable — he knew, or strongly suspected, the scenario was engineered. The woman's answer (14:19-20) is candid and flattering: yes, it was Joab; but my lord is wise as the angel of God to know all that is in the earth. The flattery is calculated: she frames David's discernment as evidence of angelic wisdom, which both confirms the deception and neutralizes David's capacity to resist — a man of angelic wisdom should act with angelic mercy.\n\nDavid's response (14:21) reveals the same paralysis the chapter opened with, now broken by social pressure rather than genuine conviction: 'I will surely do this thing.' There is no stated reason, no theological reflection, no judicial process. The return of Absalom is granted as a political concession to Joab's cleverness, not as a redemptive act grounded in either justice or genuine forgiveness. This matters enormously for what follows. Restoration granted as a political calculation rather than as a moral decision retains the moral ambiguity of its origin. David has not adjudicated the murder of Amnon; he has merely stopped refusing to let the murderer come home.\n\nJoab's prostration and blessing in 14:22 is genuine in the sense that Joab has achieved his goal. But the chapter's narrator does not celebrate. The camera immediately shifts to the qualification of verse 24. The joy of verse 22 is the joy of a man who has won a negotiation, not the joy of a father who has received a son back from the dead (cf. Luke 15:24). The difference between those two joys is the difference between what chapter 14 achieves and what it fails to achieve.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Yad* (hand, 14:19) — commonly used for agency or authorship behind an action. David's question 'is the hand of Joab with you' is a question about authorship and manipulation. *Chokhmah* (wisdom, 14:20) — the woman uses the noun form to elevate David's discernment to the level of the angelic; it is flattery designed to make refusal seem below his dignity."
