        "body": "Verse 24 is the chapter's theological center of gravity. The adversative 'however' (*wa*) signals that the concession of verse 21 comes with a qualification that transforms it. Return to Jerusalem: granted. Access to the king's face: denied. David has achieved the worst possible outcome — he has brought Absalom close enough to want what he cannot have, without the relational substance that would give the return meaning. What does 'seeing the face' of the king mean in ancient Near Eastern royal culture? It means official recognition, restored standing, access to the seat of power. To be denied the king's face in Jerusalem is to be returned to the city of power while being held in a relational limbo that is arguably more destabilizing than exile in Geshur.\n\nThe two-year period of 14:28 is the narrative's most ominous silence. The narrator does not tell us what Absalom thought or felt during those two years. The silence is pointed: nothing resolving is happening. David has made no move toward full restoration; Absalom has made no confession or acknowledgment of guilt. The half-measure sits, hardens, and festers. Reformed interpreters from Calvin onward have noted the pattern: discipline that does not proceed all the way to genuine reconciliation often produces greater rebellion than no discipline at all (cf. Calvin's commentary on 2 Samuel 14). David has neither fully forgiven (which would require a genuine process of acknowledgment and restoration) nor administered justice (which would require a trial for Amnon's murder). He has split the difference, and the result is a man living in Jerusalem who has every reason to resent and no structural reason to be loyal.\n\nThe portrait of Absalom's beauty (14:25-27) inserted between the report of his return and the report of his exclusion is not coincidental. The narrator is providing the reader with the character-profile of the man David has returned to Jerusalem without restraining or redirecting. His beauty is extraordinary; his daughter bears his murdered sister's name; his hair is already marked for narrative significance. The reader of the Succession Narrative knows that this man is the instrument by which Nathan's prophecy — 'the sword shall never depart from your house' (12:10) — will be most devastatingly fulfilled.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Paneh* (face, 14:24, 28) — in royal protocol, access to the king's face (*ra'ah paneh*) signifies restored standing and the right of petition. The phrase 'did not see the king's face' appears in verse 24 and is repeated in verse 28 to mark the duration of Absalom's exclusion. The repetition is the narrator's way of measuring the cost of David's half-measure in relational and political time."
