        "excerpt": "Therefore he said to his servants, 'See, Joab's field is next to mine, and he has barley there; go and set it on fire.'",
        "body": "The chapter's final movement reveals what half-reconciliation produces. Absalom attempts normal channels first: he sends for Joab twice (14:29). Joab refuses both times. This is remarkable — Joab, who engineered the return, now will not serve as the mediator for full access. Possibly Joab has achieved his political goal (Absalom in Jerusalem) and has no further interest in the complications of full restoration; possibly he recognizes that the king's refusal to see Absalom's face has made full access politically dangerous. Either way, Joab's unavailability leaves Absalom with no legitimate avenue to the king.\n\nAbsalom's response — burning Joab's barley field (14:30) — is the chapter's most revealing action. It is strategic, not emotional. He does not attack the palace or assemble a following; he attacks the man who controls his access to the king, in the one language that will guarantee an immediate audience. The arson works: Joab comes to Absalom, Joab goes to the king, the king summons Absalom, and the chapter ends with a kiss (14:33). But notice what the kiss is and what it is not. It is affection; it is the resumption of physical relationship; it is the formal end of exclusion. It is not justice; it is not an acknowledged reckoning with Amnon's murder; it is not a genuine accounting of Absalom's guilt; it is not a prophetically-authorized restoration. David has been coerced into a gesture of reconciliation by his son's arson. The relationship resumed under coercion is not the same as the relationship restored by genuine grace and truth.\n\nThe chapter's final posture is Absalom prostrating himself before the king (14:33) — the same prostration the woman of Tekoa used at 14:4. The gesture is ritually appropriate; the relationship it represents is hollow. Peter Leithart (A Son to Me, 2003) notes that 14:33 is the last time Absalom and David appear together in a scene of apparent peace before the rebellion of chapter 15. The kiss is followed immediately, without narrative pause, by Absalom's political campaign: 'It came about after this...' (15:1). The gap between the kiss and the rebellion is zero verses. The narrator is making a point.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Nashaq* (kissed, 14:33) — the kiss of greeting and reconciliation; used of Joseph kissing his brothers (Gen 45:15) and the father kissing the prodigal son (Luke 15:20 — the Greek *katephilesen* translates the same Semitic concept). The same gesture that in those contexts signifies genuine reconciliation here closes a chapter that has withheld the conditions for genuine reconciliation to exist."
